{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502897","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502897"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:52:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:52:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1911"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1911"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0.13,0.04,0.33,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1911"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51818"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1911"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1911"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37120"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"174"},{"type":"tags","id":"1150"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"6344"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11344"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14879"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40247"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43110"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51818"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old man is brought to his General Practitioner by his daughter, who is concerned about functional decline over the past several months. She describes periods of confusion, seeing imaginary objects and disorientation interspersed with days where he is lucid and well-oriented. He is experiencing vivid nightmares. He has had multiple falls in the past year. He has been incontinent of urine due to inability to reach the toilet in time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedical history includes hypertension, hyperlipidaemia, and type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is alert, fluent in speech, and oriented to place and person but not time. His vital signs are normal. He has no tremor. Tone is mildly increased in all limbs throughout the range of motion. Reflexes are normal and his plantar response is downgoing. His gait is slow with short, shuffling strides and a narrow base.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe scores 21/30 on a Mini Mental State Examination and is especially poor in short-term memory. His Frontal Assessment Battery is 14/18.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management option for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rivastigmine","Quetiapine","Haloperidol","Levodopa","Ventriculoperitoneal shunt insertion"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with dementia, recurrent visual hallucinations, parkinsonism (bradykinesia, limb rigidity, and typical gait disturbance), and evidence of REM sleep behavioural disorder; this constellation of features is most consistent with Lewy body dementia (LBD). LBD is characterised by fluctuating cognitive deficits, persistent detailed visual hallucinations, parkinsonian features, and REM sleep behavioural phenomena.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECholinesterase inhibitors (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Erivastigmine\u003C/strong\u003E, donepezil) have been shown to have mild to moderate potential benefit on cognition, fluctuations, hallucinations, and parkinsonian symptoms in LBD, and are generally well-tolerated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA highly specific feature of the condition is extreme sensitivity to anti-psychotic medication, which might otherwise be considered to assist with managing problematic behaviour in dementia patients, but in LBD patients can precipitate severe extra-pyramidal symptoms or even neuroleptic malignant syndrome. Typical antipsychotics (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaloperidol\u003C/strong\u003E) should be avoided entirely. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAtypical antipsychotics (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Equetiapine\u003C/strong\u003E) should only be used under specialist guidance at low doses for severe, disabling psychosis. Though \u003Cstrong\u003Elevodopa\u003C/strong\u003E is indeed often used in LBD patients, it is typically indicated in the setting of problematic parkinsonian features, such as disabling tremor or significant gait instability causing falls.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe role of \u003Cstrong\u003Eventriculoperitoneal shunt insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is well established in patient\u0027s suffering from a symptomatic normal pressure hydrocephalus, of which this patient has some characteristic features including evolving new cognitive impairment and urinary incontinence. The gait would classically be described as broad based with diminished foot clearance, rather than narrow. However there would need to be objective evidence of clinical improvement with a large volume lumbar puncture and removal of  cerebrospinal fluid, prior to consideration of shunt insertion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A cholinesterase inhibitor is the treatment of choice for patients with Lewy body dementia."],"references":["Hershey, L.A., Coleman-Jackson, R. Pharmacological Management of Dementia with Lewy Bodies.\u00a0Drugs Aging\u00a036,\u00a0309\u2013319 (2019)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37120"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1911"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37120"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-29T23:40:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-29T23:44:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1911"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51818"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self